    ("What is the perimeter of a rectangle with length 12 and width 5?", "P = 2(length + width)\nP = 2(12 + 5) = 2(17) = 34\n\nThe perimeter is 34 units.", "geometry", 1),
    ("Find the area of a trapezoid with bases 6 and 10 and height 4", "A = ½(b₁ + b₂) × h\nA = ½(6 + 10) × 4\nA = ½(16) × 4\nA = 8 × 4 = 32\n\nThe area is 32 square units.", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the surface area of a sphere with radius 5?", "A = 4πr²\nA = 4π(25) = 100π ≈ 314.16\n\nThe surface area is 100π square units, about 314.", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the volume of a sphere with radius 3?", "V = (4/3)πr³\nV = (4/3)π(27) = 36π ≈ 113.1\n\nThe volume is 36π cubic units, about 113.", "geometry", 2),
    ("A right triangle has a hypotenuse of 13 and one leg of 5. Find the other leg.", "Pythagorean theorem: a² + b² = c²\n5² + b² = 13²\n25 + b² = 169\nb² = 144\nb = 12\n\nThe other leg is 12. This is a 5-12-13 Pythagorean triple!", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the distance between points (1, 3) and (4, 7)?", "Distance formula: d = √((x₂-x₁)² + (y₂-y₁)²)\n\nd = √((4-1)² + (7-3)²)\nd = √(3² + 4²)\nd = √(9 + 16)\nd = √25 = 5\n\nThe distance is 5 units.", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the midpoint between (2, 4) and (8, 10)?", "Midpoint formula: M = ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2)\n\nM = ((2+8)/2, (4+10)/2)\nM = (10/2, 14/2)\nM = (5, 7)\n\nThe midpoint is (5, 7).", "geometry", 1),
    ("What are the special right triangles?", "Two important ones to memorize:\n\n45-45-90 triangle:\n- Angles: 45°, 45°, 90°\n- Sides: 1, 1, √2\n- If legs = x, hypotenuse = x√2\n\n30-60-90 triangle:\n- Angles: 30°, 60°, 90°\n- Sides: 1, √3, 2\n- If short leg = x, long leg = x√3, hypotenuse = 2x\n\nPythagorean triples (integer sides):\n3-4-5 (and multiples: 6-8-10, 9-12-15...)\n5-12-13\n8-15-17\n7-24-25\n\nThese show up constantly on tests — memorize them!", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the equation of a circle?", "Standard form: (x - h)² + (y - k)² = r²\n\nCenter at (h, k), radius r.\n\nExamples:\n- x² + y² = 25 → center (0,0), radius 5\n- (x - 3)² + (y + 2)² = 16 → center (3,-2), radius 4\n\nIf given expanded form: x² + y² + Dx + Ey + F = 0\nComplete the square to get back to standard form.\n\nExample: x² + y² - 6x + 4y - 12 = 0\n(x² - 6x + 9) + (y² + 4y + 4) = 12 + 9 + 4\n(x - 3)² + (y + 2)² = 25\nCenter (3, -2), radius 5", "geometry", 3),
    ("What is the law of sines?", "a/sin(A) = b/sin(B) = c/sin(C)\n\nUse when you know:\n- Two angles and a side (AAS or ASA)\n- Two sides and an angle opposite one of them (SSA — ambiguous case!)\n\nExample: In triangle ABC, A = 40°, B = 75°, a = 10. Find b.\nC = 180° - 40° - 75° = 65°\n\n10/sin(40°) = b/sin(75°)\nb = 10 × sin(75°)/sin(40°)\nb = 10 × 0.966/0.643\nb ≈ 15.02\n\nWarning — SSA ambiguous case: Given two sides and a non-included angle, there could be 0, 1, or 2 valid triangles. Always check!", "geometry", 3),
    ("What are radians?", "Radians are another way to measure angles, based on the arc length.\n\n1 radian = the angle where the arc length equals the radius.\n\nFull circle = 2π radians = 360°\nHalf circle = π radians = 180°\n\nConversions:\n- Degrees to radians: multiply by π/180\n- Radians to degrees: multiply by 180/π\n\nCommon values:\n0° = 0 rad\n30° = π/6\n45° = π/4\n60° = π/3\n90° = π/2\n180° = π rad\n270° = 3π/2\n360° = 2π rad\n\nWhy use radians?\n- Calculus formulas only work in radians\n- sin(x) ≈ x for small x in radians (but not degrees)\n- Arc length = rθ (in radians) — simple formula\n- Unit circle: angle in radians equals the arc length", "geometry", 3),
    ("Find the equation of a line passing through (2, 3) and (6, 11)", "Step 1: Find slope\nm = (y₂ - y₁)/(x₂ - x₁) = (11 - 3)/(6 - 2) = 8/4 = 2\n\nStep 2: Use point-slope form\ny - y₁ = m(x - x₁)\ny - 3 = 2(x - 2)\ny - 3 = 2x - 4\ny = 2x - 1\n\nOr in standard form: 2x - y = 1\n\nCheck: (2,3) → 2(2) - 1 = 3 ✓\n(6,11) → 2(6) - 1 = 11 ✓", "geometry", 2),
    ("What is the volume of a cone with radius 4 and height 9?", "V = (1/3)πr²h\nV = (1/3)π(16)(9)\nV = (1/3)π(144)\nV = 48π ≈ 150.8\n\nThe volume is 48π cubic units, about 151.\n\nNote: A cone's volume is exactly 1/3 of a cylinder with the same base and height.", "geometry", 2),
    ("What are similar triangles?", "Similar triangles have the same shape but different sizes.\n\nConditions for similarity:\n1. AA: Two angles match (third automatically matches too)\n2. SAS: Two sides proportional AND included angle matches\n3. SSS: All three sides proportional\n\nIf similar with scale factor k:\n- All sides are k times longer\n- All angles are the same\n- Area is k² times larger\n- Volume (if 3D) is k³ times larger\n\nExample: Triangle with sides 3-4-5 is similar to one with sides 6-8-10 (scale factor 2).\nArea of 6-8-10 = 4 × area of 3-4-5", "geometry", 3),

