    ("What is a variable in programming?", "A variable is a named container that stores a value in memory.\n\nThink of it like a labeled box:\n- name = \"Alice\" → a box labeled 'name' containing the string \"Alice\"\n- age = 25 → a box labeled 'age' containing the number 25\n\nKey concepts:\n- Declaration: creating the variable (some languages require this)\n- Assignment: giving it a value (x = 5)\n- Type: what kind of data it holds (number, string, boolean, etc.)\n- Scope: where in the code the variable is accessible\n\nStatic typing (Java, C++): type must be declared\nint age = 25;\n\nDynamic typing (Python, JavaScript): type is inferred\nage = 25\n\nVariables can be reassigned:\nx = 5\nx = 10  # x is now 10", "cs", 1),
    ("What is a loop?", "A loop repeats a block of code multiple times.\n\nFor loop (known number of times):\nfor i in range(5):\n    print(i)  # prints 0, 1, 2, 3, 4\n\nWhile loop (repeat while condition is true):\ncount = 0\nwhile count < 5:\n    print(count)\n    count += 1\n\nCommon patterns:\n- Counting: repeat N times\n- Accumulating: sum = 0; for each item: sum += item\n- Searching: loop until you find what you need\n- Processing: do something to every item in a collection\n\nDangers:\n- Infinite loop: condition never becomes false\n- Off-by-one: loop runs one too many or too few times\n- Modifying collection while iterating over it", "cs", 1),
    ("What is an array?", "An array is an ordered collection of items stored contiguously in memory.\n\nKey properties:\n- Indexed: access items by position (0-based in most languages)\n- Fixed size (in static arrays) or dynamic (in Python lists, JavaScript arrays)\n- Fast access: O(1) to read/write any element by index\n\nExample:\nfruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\nfruits[0] → \"apple\"\nfruits[1] → \"banana\"\nfruits[2] → \"cherry\"\n\nCommon operations:\n- Access by index: O(1)\n- Search for value: O(n)\n- Insert at end: O(1) amortized\n- Insert at beginning: O(n) — must shift all elements\n- Delete from middle: O(n) — must shift elements\n\nThis is why inserting at the beginning of a large array is slow!", "cs", 2),
    ("What is a linked list?", "A linked list stores data in nodes, where each node points to the next one.\n\nStructure:\n[Data|Next] → [Data|Next] → [Data|Next] → null\n\nvs Array:\nArray: [a][b][c][d] (contiguous memory)\nLinked List: [a]→[b]→[c]→[d] (scattered memory, linked by pointers)\n\nOperations:\n- Access by index: O(n) — must traverse from head\n- Insert at head: O(1) — just update pointer\n- Insert at tail: O(n) without tail pointer, O(1) with\n- Delete: O(n) to find, O(1) to remove (just redirect pointers)\n\nWhen to use linked list over array:\n- Frequent insertions/deletions at the beginning\n- Unknown size that changes frequently\n- Don't need random access\n\nWhen to use array over linked list:\n- Need fast access by index\n- Memory efficiency (no pointer overhead)\n- Cache locality matters (arrays are cache-friendly)", "cs", 3),
    ("What is a binary search tree?", "A BST is a tree where each node has at most 2 children:\n- Left child's value < parent's value\n- Right child's value > parent's value\n\nExample:\n      8\n     / \\\n    3   10\n   / \\    \\\n  1   6   14\n\nOperations (average case):\n- Search: O(log n) — at each node, go left or right\n- Insert: O(log n) — find the right spot, add it\n- Delete: O(log n) — three cases (leaf, one child, two children)\n\nWorst case (unbalanced): O(n) — degenerates into a linked list\n\nTraversal orders:\n- In-order (left, root, right): gives sorted output\n- Pre-order (root, left, right): copies the tree\n- Post-order (left, right, root): deletes the tree\n\nBalanced variants (AVL, Red-Black) guarantee O(log n) by self-balancing after insertions.", "cs", 3),
    ("What is sorting? Explain common algorithms", "Sorting = arranging items in order (ascending or descending).\n\nO(n²) algorithms (simple but slow for large data):\n\nBubble Sort: Swap adjacent items if out of order. Repeat until sorted.\n- Simple but very slow. O(n²) average and worst.\n\nSelection Sort: Find minimum, swap to front. Repeat for remaining.\n- Always O(n²), never better.\n\nInsertion Sort: Insert each item into its correct position.\n- O(n²) worst, but O(n) for nearly sorted data. Good for small arrays.\n\nO(n log n) algorithms (efficient):\n\nMerge Sort: Split in half, sort each half, merge.\n- Always O(n log n), stable, needs O(n) extra space.\n\nQuick Sort: Pick pivot, partition, recurse.\n- O(n log n) average, O(n²) worst, in-place, very fast in practice.\n\nHeap Sort: Build max heap, extract max repeatedly.\n- O(n log n) guaranteed, in-place, not stable.\n\nPractical choice: Most languages use Timsort (hybrid of merge + insertion) or a tuned quicksort.", "cs", 3),
    ("What is a stack and a queue?", "Stack: Last In, First Out (LIFO)\n- Like a stack of plates — you add and remove from the top\n- Push: add to top\n- Pop: remove from top\n- Peek: look at top without removing\n- All operations: O(1)\n\nUses: function call stack, undo/redo, expression evaluation, backtracking\n\nQueue: First In, First Out (FIFO)\n- Like a line at a store — first person in line is first served\n- Enqueue: add to back\n- Dequeue: remove from front\n- All operations: O(1)\n\nUses: task scheduling, BFS (breadth-first search), print queues, message queues\n\nComparison:\nStack: abc in → cba out (last one in, first one out)\nQueue: abc in → abc out (first one in, first one out)\n\nDeque (double-ended queue): can add/remove from both ends. Combines stack + queue.", "cs", 2),
    ("What is an API?", "API = Application Programming Interface\n\nA set of rules that allows different programs to communicate.\n\nAnalogy: A restaurant menu.\n- You (client) look at the menu (API documentation)\n- You order (make a request)\n- The kitchen (server) prepares your food\n- The waiter (API) delivers it (response)\n- You don't need to know how the kitchen works\n\nTypes:\n- REST API: Uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) with URLs\n- GraphQL: Query exactly what you need, nothing more\n- WebSocket: Real-time two-way communication\n- Library API: Functions you call in code (like math.sqrt())\n\nREST example:\nGET /api/users → list all users\nGET /api/users/123 → get user 123\nPOST /api/users → create a new user\nDELETE /api/users/123 → delete user 123\n\nAPIs are how modern apps work — your weather app calls a weather API, your game calls a server API, etc.", "cs", 2),
    ("What is a database?", "A database is an organized collection of data, designed for efficient storage and retrieval.\n\nTwo main types:\n\nRelational (SQL):\n- Data in tables with rows and columns\n- Strict schema (defined structure)\n- Relationships between tables (foreign keys)\n- ACID transactions (reliable)\n- Examples: PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite\n\nQuery: SELECT name, age FROM users WHERE age > 18\n\nNoSQL (non-relational):\n- Flexible schema (documents, key-value, graph)\n- Better for unstructured or rapidly changing data\n- Often faster for simple lookups\n- Examples: MongoDB (documents), Redis (key-value), Neo4j (graph)\n\nQuery: db.users.find({age: {$gt: 18}})\n\nWhen to use SQL:\n- Data has clear relationships\n- Need complex queries and joins\n- Need strong consistency (banking, orders)\n\nWhen to use NoSQL:\n- Schema changes frequently\n- Need horizontal scaling\n- Working with documents or cache", "cs", 3),
    ("What is object-oriented programming?", "OOP organizes code around objects that combine data and behavior.\n\nFour pillars:\n\n1. Encapsulation: Bundle data + methods, hide internals\n   class Dog:\n       def __init__(self, name):\n           self._name = name  # private\n       def bark(self):\n           return f\"{self._name} says woof!\"\n\n2. Inheritance: Child classes inherit from parent\n   class GuideDog(Dog):  # Gets all Dog abilities + adds its own\n       def guide(self):\n           return \"Leading the way\"\n\n3. Polymorphism: Same interface, different behavior\n   class Cat:\n       def speak(self): return \"Meow\"\n   class Dog:\n       def speak(self): return \"Woof\"\n   # Same method name, different output\n\n4. Abstraction: Hide complexity, show essentials\n   You call car.start() without knowing the engine details\n\nBenefits: Code reuse, modularity, easier maintenance, models real-world entities\nTrade-offs: More code upfront, can be over-engineered, performance overhead", "cs", 3),
    ("What is recursion vs iteration?", "Both solve problems by repeating steps, but differently:\n\nRecursion: Function calls itself\n- Base case stops it\n- Elegant for: trees, divide-and-conquer, mathematical definitions\n- Uses call stack (can overflow for deep recursion)\n- Often slower (function call overhead)\n\ndef factorial(n):\n    if n == 0: return 1\n    return n * factorial(n-1)\n\nIteration: Uses loops (for, while)\n- Explicit stopping condition\n- Better for: simple repetition, linear traversal\n- No stack overflow risk\n- Usually faster (no function call overhead)\n\ndef factorial(n):\n    result = 1\n    for i in range(1, n+1):\n        result *= i\n    return result\n\nWhen recursion is better:\n- Tree traversals (binary tree DFS)\n- Problems naturally defined recursively (Fibonacci, fractals)\n- Divide and conquer (merge sort, quick sort)\n\nWhen iteration is better:\n- Simple counting or accumulation\n- Performance matters\n- Deep recursion could overflow stack\n\nAny recursion can be rewritten as iteration (and vice versa), but some problems are much more natural one way.", "cs", 2),
    ("What is a graph in computer science?", "A graph = nodes (vertices) connected by edges.\n\nTypes:\n- Undirected: edges go both ways (friendships, roads)\n- Directed: edges have direction (follows, one-way streets)\n- Weighted: edges have costs (distances, prices)\n- Unweighted: all edges are equal\n\nRepresentations:\n- Adjacency matrix: 2D array, 1 if edge exists, 0 if not. O(V²) space.\n- Adjacency list: each node stores list of neighbors. O(V+E) space. More common.\n\nKey algorithms:\n- BFS (Breadth-First Search): level by level. Finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. Uses a queue.\n- DFS (Depth-First Search): go deep first. Good for connectivity, cycles, topological sort. Uses a stack (or recursion).\n- Dijkstra's: shortest path in weighted graphs (no negative weights)\n- A*: Dijkstra's with a heuristic (used in GPS navigation, game AI)\n\nReal uses: social networks, maps/GPS, web crawling, recommendation systems, network routing", "cs", 3),
    ("What is version control / Git?", "Version control tracks changes to code over time.\n\nGit basics:\n- Repository (repo): project folder with full history\n- Commit: a snapshot of changes with a message\n- Branch: parallel version for new features\n- Merge: combine branches back together\n\nWorkflow:\n1. git init — create a repo\n2. git add file.py — stage changes\n3. git commit -m 'Add feature' — save snapshot\n4. git branch feature — create a branch\n5. git checkout feature — switch to it\n6. git merge feature — combine into main\n\nWhy it matters:\n- Time machine: revert to any previous version\n- Collaboration: multiple people work simultaneously\n- Branching: try things without breaking main code\n- Blame: see who changed what and when\n\nGitHub/GitLab: cloud hosting for Git repos + collaboration features (PRs, issues, CI/CD)\n\nConflicts: When two people edit the same line, Git can't auto-merge. You manually resolve, then commit.", "cs", 2),
    ("What is the difference between compiled and interpreted languages?", "Compiled:\n- Source code → compiler → machine code → run\n- Fast execution (already translated)\n- Errors caught before running\n- Examples: C, C++, Rust, Go\n\nInterpreted:\n- Source code → interpreter → run directly (line by line)\n- Slower execution (translated on the fly)\n- More flexible (dynamic typing, eval)\n- Examples: Python, JavaScript, Ruby\n\nHybrid (JIT — Just In Time):\n- Source code → bytecode → JIT compiler → machine code at runtime\n- Best of both: portability + speed\n- Examples: Java (JVM), C# (CLR), JavaScript (V8 engine)\n\nTrade-offs:\n- Compiled: faster, catches errors early, less portable\n- Interpreted: slower, more flexible, highly portable\n- JIT: good performance after warmup, portable bytecode\n\nIn practice, the distinction is blurry — Python has compiled bytecode (.pyc), and C can be interpreted with the right tool. The key difference is when translation to machine code happens.", "cs", 2),

